<section id="the-fasting-dogma" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Dogma That Starved Patients for Decades</h2>
  <p>For most of the twentieth century, the logic of pancreatitis management was intuitive to the point of seeming self-evident: the pancreas secretes digestive enzymes in response to food; the pancreas is inflamed; therefore, stop feeding the patient, rest the gland, let it recover. Nil by mouth. Nasogastric tubes. Sometimes weeks of parenteral nutrition.</p>
  <p>The logic was wrong.</p>
  <p>Clinical trials have now established that early oral feeding — initiated within 24 hours of admission in mild-to-moderate cases — supports recovery and leads to shorter hospital stays. A 2025 review in the <em>United European Gastroenterology Journal</em> summarized the evidence: early oral feeding is now the standard of care for mild-to-moderate acute pancreatitis, overturning the historical fasting approach. The mechanism is not counterintuitive once you understand it. The gut barrier requires luminal nutrition to maintain integrity; prolonged fasting promotes bacterial translocation, which amplifies systemic inflammation. Feeding the patient, it turns out, helps protect the pancreas from the secondary damage that fasting was supposed to prevent.</p>
  <p>The caveat matters: in severe acute pancreatitis, the picture is less clear. Trials show early feeding is not demonstrably superior to later on-demand feeding in severe cases, limiting the generalizability of the early-feeding paradigm. The 2025 IAP guidelines reflect this nuance. But in mild-to-moderate disease — which represents the majority of cases — the old dogma has been cleanly overturned. Medicine ran the trials it should have run twenty years earlier and found that its intuition was backward.</p>
  <p>This is worth dwelling on, not as a curiosity, but as a structural indictment. The fasting dogma persisted for decades not because evidence supported it, but because no one ran the trials to challenge it. Pancreatitis, despite its prevalence and its burden, attracted remarkably little rigorous therapeutic investigation. The disease was common, painful, and largely managed with supportive care — and that combination, perversely, may have reduced the urgency to study it more carefully.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The fasting dogma persisted for decades not because evidence supported it, but because no one ran the trials to challenge it. Pancreatitis attracted remarkably little rigorous therapeutic investigation for a disease this prevalent."</p></aside>

<section id="olezarsen" class="reveal">
  <h2>The First Drug That Actually Prevents It</h2>
  <p>In November 2025, results from the CORE-TIMI 72a and 72b trials were presented at the American Heart Association Scientific Sessions. Olezarsen, an RNA-targeted therapy that inhibits apolipoprotein C-III — a protein that impairs triglyceride clearance — reduced acute pancreatitis incidence by 85% in patients with severe hypertriglyceridemia. The trial was published in the <em>New England Journal of Medicine</em>. Nicholas A. Marston, MD, the trial's lead investigator, stated: "The primary purpose of triglyceride lowering in patients with severe hypertriglyceridemia is to reduce the risk of acute pancreatitis, which can be life-threatening. Our trials showed that olezarsen reduced the incidence of acute pancreatitis by 85% among patients with severe hypertriglyceridemia."</p>
  <p>Eighty-five percent is a landmark number. It is also a number that requires immediate qualification.</p>
  <p>Hypertriglyceridemia-induced pancreatitis accounts for roughly 1 to 4 percent of all acute pancreatitis cases. The CORE-TIMI 72 population — patients with severe hypertriglyceridemia, defined as triglycerides above 500 mg/dL — is a specific, high-risk subgroup. Olezarsen is not a treatment for the gallstone-induced pancreatitis that accounts for the largest share of cases, nor for the alcohol-induced pancreatitis that is the second most common cause, nor for the idiopathic cases that make up a substantial remainder. The 2025 IAP guidelines are explicit: no targeted anti-inflammatory therapies for acute pancreatitis currently exist. The guidelines identify such therapies as the primary future research priority — and then acknowledge that the cupboard is bare.</p>
  <p>The significance of olezarsen is therefore not that it solves pancreatitis. It is that it is the first drug to demonstrably prevent pancreatitis events in any population, in a human randomized controlled trial. That distinction matters because of what it reveals about the therapeutic landscape. For a disease that hospitalizes 275,000 Americans annually, that has been rising in global incidence for three decades, and that carries a documented pathway to one of the deadliest cancers in medicine — the first preventive drug arrived in 2025, for a subgroup representing a small fraction of patients. That is not a triumph. It is a measure of how little this disease has been prioritized.</p>
  <p>The rodent model problem is not incidental here. The <em>Theranostics</em> review published in 2026 notes that most mechanistic pancreatitis research has been conducted in experimental animal models, and treatments that showed efficacy in those models have shown variable and often disappointing results in human trials. The trypsin-centric model of pathogenesis — premature trypsinogen activation as the primary driver — has itself been challenged by experiments showing persistent pancreatic damage even in the absence of trypsinogen activation, suggesting parallel mechanisms that complicate drug targeting. The biology is harder than the models suggested. Olezarsen works because it targets a specific, well-validated metabolic mechanism — apolipoprotein C-III inhibition reducing triglyceride levels — rather than the inflammatory cascade itself. It is a workaround, not a solution.</p>
</section>

<section id="glp1-controversy" class="reveal">
  <h2>The GLP-1 Question: Not Closed</h2>
  <p>GLP-1 receptor agonists — semaglutide, tirzepatide, liraglutide — are now among the most widely prescribed drugs in the world. They are prescribed for obesity, Type 2 diabetes, and increasingly for cardiovascular risk reduction. They are also prescribed, frequently, to patients who have had pancreatitis. That intersection is where the controversy lives.</p>
  <p>The concern is not new. Early clinical trials flagged a signal: GLP-1 receptor agonists appeared to slightly elevate pancreatitis risk. The FDA issued warnings. Prescribers were cautious, or should have been. The mechanism was biologically plausible — GLP-1 receptors are expressed in pancreatic tissue, and the drugs affect pancreatic secretion and ductal pressure.</p>
  <p>The subsequent evidence has substantially, though not definitively, shifted the picture. Large meta-analyses of clinical trial data do not support a class-wide pancreatitis risk for GLP-1 receptor agonists, according to a 2025 review in the <em>Cleveland Clinic Journal of Medicine</em>. A Cleveland Clinic cohort study of 161 patients with prior pancreatitis who were prescribed GLP-1 drugs found that only 10% experienced recurrent pancreatitis — a rate no greater than the general population baseline. Mahmoud Nassar, MD, PhD, at the University at Buffalo, presenting at the Endocrine Society's 2024 meeting, argued that GLP-1 receptor agonists may actually reduce the risk of acute pancreatitis recurrence in patients with obesity and Type 2 diabetes, challenging previous concerns.</p>
  <p>The honest position is this: the debate is not closed. Early signals were real. Some real-world data still suggest caution in specific high-risk patients. The large meta-analyses are reassuring but not exonerating. A 10% recurrence rate in a Cleveland Clinic cohort of 161 patients is striking, but 161 patients is not a definitive sample. The biology remains contested. Prescribing GLP-1 drugs to a patient with a history of pancreatitis is a clinical judgment call that requires weighing documented metabolic benefits against an unresolved risk signal — and that is precisely the kind of uncertainty that medicine is bad at communicating and patients are bad at tolerating. Neither reflexive avoidance nor uncritical enthusiasm is the appropriate response. The evidence has shifted. The debate has not ended.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"For a disease that hospitalizes 275,000 Americans annually and carries a documented pathway to pancreatic cancer, the first preventive drug arrived in 2025, for a subgroup representing a small fraction of patients. That is not a triumph. It is a measure of how little this disease has been prioritized."</p></aside>

<section id="emerging-science" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Is Actually Coming</h2>
  <p>The 2026 <em>Theranostics</em> review of anti-inflammatory therapeutic strategies identifies the emerging pipeline: targeted nanomedicine for drug delivery to inflamed pancreatic tissue, gene therapies aimed at the NF-κB pathway and cytokine overexpression, and stem cell-based approaches for reducing inflammation and promoting tissue regeneration. A 2025 meta-analysis found that stem cell-derived extracellular vesicles showed promise in severe acute pancreatitis models. The calcium signaling pathway — the upstream trigger of the entire autodigestion cascade — remains an active target, as does mitochondrial dysfunction and ATP depletion in early-phase disease.</p>
  <p>The pediatric dimension adds a layer of urgency that has not received proportionate attention. A systematic review and meta-analysis published in <em>Gastroenterology</em> in 2021 found that pediatric acute pancreatitis incidence is rising at an average annual percent change of 5.44% — faster than adult incidence. The drivers are not fully understood. Obesity is implicated. So are genetic mutations in trypsinogen and CFTR genes that predispose younger patients to recurrent and chronic disease. A child who develops chronic pancreatitis at twelve has decades of progressive gland destruction ahead of them.</p>
  <p>Eastern Europe has surpassed North America to record the highest age-standardized incidence and death rates for pancreatitis globally, per the GBD 2021 analysis — driven primarily by elevated alcohol consumption and, likely, later access to the supportive care improvements that have modestly reduced mortality in wealthier health systems. The global burden is not distributed evenly, and the therapeutic advances that are arriving — olezarsen, early feeding protocols, improved endoscopic management of biliary causes — are arriving first where the disease is least severe.</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">What Has Actually Changed in Pancreatitis Management</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Overturned:</strong> Fasting to "rest" the pancreas — early oral feeding now standard in mild-to-moderate cases (UEGJ, 2025)</li>
    <li><strong>First preventive drug:</strong> Olezarsen reduces pancreatitis events by 85% in severe hypertriglyceridemia patients — but only in that subgroup (NEJM / CORE-TIMI 72, 2025)</li>
    <li><strong>GLP-1 risk signal:</strong> Substantially revised downward by meta-analyses; Cleveland Clinic cohort shows 10% recurrence in prior pancreatitis patients — but debate is not closed</li>
    <li><strong>Cancer screening trigger:</strong> New-onset diabetes + unexplained weight loss in pancreatitis patient = prompt pancreatic cancer evaluation (Chari, MD Anderson)</li>
    <li><strong>Still absent:</strong> Any approved targeted anti-inflammatory therapy for acute pancreatitis — identified as the primary research gap by IAP 2025 guidelines</li>
    <li><strong>Emerging:</strong> Nanomedicine delivery, NF-κB-targeted gene therapies, stem cell-derived extracellular vesicles (Theranostics, 2026)</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="the-gap" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Gap That Remains</h2>
  <p>The 2025 International Association of Pancreatology guidelines represent the most comprehensive evidence synthesis this disease has ever received — 96 questions, contributions from the world's leading pancreatologists, covering everything from fluid resuscitation protocols to endoscopic management of walled-off necrosis. They are a genuine achievement. They also contain, buried in the section on future research priorities, an admission that is more revealing than any of the recommendations: the primary areas identified for future investigation are targeted therapies for controlling systemic inflammation and mitigating organ dysfunction in acute pancreatitis. The guidelines then acknowledge that no such approved therapies currently exist.</p>
  <p>Read that again. The leading international guidelines for a disease that is the most common GI cause of hospitalization in the United States, that has been rising in global incidence for thirty years, that carries a documented pipeline to chronic disease, diabetes, and one of the most lethal cancers in medicine — those guidelines identify the control of systemic inflammation as the primary research priority, and then note that medicine has not yet produced a single approved drug to accomplish it.</p>
  <p>Medicine has made real progress. The fasting dogma is dead, at least in mild-to-moderate disease. Olezarsen has demonstrated that prevention is pharmacologically achievable, in a specific population. The GLP-1 panic has been substantially revised by evidence. The cancer risk signals are better characterized and, crucially, better actionable — the combination of new-onset diabetes and unexplained weight loss in a pancreatitis patient now has a clinical protocol attached to it. The rodent model failures have pushed researchers toward human trial designs. These are not nothing.</p>
  <p>But the patient admitted today with severe necrotizing pancreatitis — the 25% of cases that progress to severe disease, carrying a mortality rate of 20 to 30% — receives treatment that is structurally similar to what was available in 1995. Aggressive fluid resuscitation. Nutritional support. Management of complications. Watchful waiting. The inflammatory cascade that is destroying their pancreatic tissue in real time has no approved pharmacological target. The NF-κB pathway is well-characterized. The cytokine storm is well-documented. The calcium signaling trigger is understood. And there is nothing in the approved formulary that addresses any of it.</p>
  <p>The pancreas, it turns out, is harder to rescue than it is to lose. Medicine is finally running the right trials, asking the right questions, and overturning its worst assumptions. It is thirty years late, and for the patient in the ICU with necrotizing pancreatitis, that lateness is not an abstraction.</p>
</section>

